## 20.1 Framework Directory Structure
```
deerflow-agent-framework/
├── .cursorrules                  ← THIS FILE (root constraints)
├── deerflow/
│   ├── context.md                ← Session state tracking (auto-managed)
│   ├── rules/                    ← Detailed rules and standards
│   │   ├── code-quality.md       ← Code quality rules (expanded)
│   │   ├── security.md           ← Security rules (expanded)
│   │   ├── testing.md            ← Testing rules (expanded)
│   │   ├── ui-ux.md              ← UI/UX rules (expanded)
│   │   ├── dependencies.md       ← Dependency management rules (expanded)
│   │   ├── error-handling.md     ← Error handling patterns (expanded)
│   │   └── naming-conventions.md ← Naming standards (expanded)
│   ├── workflows/                ← Workflow definitions
│   │   ├── deerflow-cycle.md     ← Detailed Deerflow Cycle workflow
│   │   ├── feature-development.md ← Feature development workflow
│   │   ├── bug-fixing.md         ← Bug fixing workflow
│   │   ├── refactoring.md        ← Refactoring workflow
│   │   └── deployment.md         ← Deployment workflow
│   ├── skills/                   ← Agent skill definitions
│   │   ├── code-generation.md    ← Code generation skills
│   │   ├── code-review.md        ← Code review skills
│   │   ├── debugging.md          ← Debugging skills
│   │   ├── database.md           ← Database skills
│   │   ├── api-design.md         ← API design skills
│   │   ├── frontend.md           ← Frontend skills
│   │   ├── backend.md            ← Backend skills
│   │   ├── devops.md             ← DevOps skills
│   │   ├── security.md           ← Security skills
│   │   ├── testing.md            ← Testing skills
│   │   ├── performance.md        ← Performance skills
│   │   └── git.md                ← Git skills
│   ├── core/                     ← Core engine implementations
│   │   ├── engine.md             ← Core engine architecture
│   │   ├── quality-gates.md      ← Quality gate implementations
│   │   ├── context-manager.md    ← Context management system
│   │   └── penalty-system.md     ← Penalty system implementation
│   ├── algorithms/               ← Algorithmic constraints
│   │   ├── complexity-limits.md  ← Time/space complexity limits
│   │   ├── loop-safety.md        ← Loop safety constraints
│   │   ├── data-structures.md    ← Data structure selection guide
│   │   └── patterns.md           ← Design patterns catalog
│   ├── mcp/                      ← MCP tool integrations
│   │   ├── tools-config.json     ← MCP tool configurations
│   │   ├── quality-tools.md      ← Quality assurance tool definitions
│   │   ├── search-tools.md       ← Search tool definitions
│   │   └── test-tools.md         ← Testing tool definitions
│   ├── backups/                  ← Automatic backups (auto-managed)
│   │   └── <timestamp>/          ← Timestamped backup directories
│   └── logs/                     ← Session logs (auto-managed)
│       ├── violations.log        ← Violation log
│       ├── deletions.log         ← Deletion log
│       ├── moves.log             ← File move/rename log
│       └── quality-gates.log     ← Quality gate results log
```

## 20.2 Mandatory Reading Order
When starting a new session, the agent should read files in this order:
1. `.cursorrules` (this file) — Core constraints
2. `deerflow/context.md` — Current session state (if exists)
3. `deerflow/rules/` — Relevant rule files for the current task
4. `deerflow/workflows/` — Relevant workflow for the current task type
5. `deerflow/skills/` — Relevant skills for the current task

## 20.3 File Priority
- This `.cursorrules` file takes precedence over ALL other configuration files.
- Rules in `deerflow/rules/` expand on this file but cannot contradict it.
- Workflow files define processes but must follow all rules.
- Skill files provide capabilities but must operate within all constraints.

## 20.4 Version Information
- **Version**: 1.0.0
- **Last Updated**: 2026-01-15
- **Compatible Agents**: Cursor, GitHub Copilot, Claude Code, Windsurf, Aider,
  Continue, Cline, and any agent supporting .cursorrules or equivalent format.
- **Framework License**: MIT

## 20.5 Extension Points
This framework is designed to be extensible:
- Add new rules in `deerflow/rules/` — they'll be picked up by the context manager.
- Add new workflows in `deerflow/workflows/` — they'll be matched to task types.
- Add new skills in `deerflow/skills/` — they'll be loaded when relevant.
- Add new MCP tools in `deerflow/mcp/` — they'll be available for use.
- Add new algorithms in `deerflow/algorithms/` — they'll enforce constraints.

